[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions can help a programmer read the code, help a compiler compile it, or help the program detect its own defects.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] For the latter, some programs check assertions by actually evaluating the predicate as they run.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Then, if it is not in fact true – an assertion failure – the program considers itself to be broken and typically deliberately crashes or throws an assertion failure exception.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Programmers can use assertions to help specify programs and to reason about program correctness.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] For example, a precondition—an assertion placed at the beginning of a section of code—determines the set of states under which the programmer expects the code to execute.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] A postcondition—placed at the end—describes the expected state at the end of execution.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The example above uses the notation for including assertions used by C.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] That notation cannot be used in existing mainstream programming languages.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] However, programmers can include unchecked assertions using the comment feature of their programming language.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The braces included in the comment help distinguish this use of a comment from other uses.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Libraries may provide assertion features as well.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Several modern programming languages include checked assertions – statements that are checked at runtime or sometimes statically.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] If an assertion evaluates to false at runtime, an assertion failure results, which typically causes execution to abort.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This draws attention to the location at which the logical inconsistency is detected and can be preferable to the behaviour that would otherwise result.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The use of assertions helps the programmer design, develop, and reason about a program.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In languages such as Eiffel, assertions form part of the design process; other languages, such as C and Java, use them only to check assumptions at runtime.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In both cases, they can be checked for validity at runtime, but can usually also be suppressed.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions can function as a form of documentation: they can describe the state the code expects to find before it runs (its preconditions), and the state the code expects to result in when it is finished running (postconditions); they can also specify invariants of a class.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Eiffel integrates such assertions into the language and automatically extracts them to document the class.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This forms an important part of the method of design by contract.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This approach is also useful in languages that do not explicitly support it: the advantage of using assertion statements rather than assertions in comments is that the program can check the assertions every time it runs; if the assertion no longer holds, an error can be reported.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This prevents the code from getting out of sync with the assertions.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] For example, the following demonstrates design by contract in C++ (using C++26 contracts).
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] An assertion may be used to verify that an assumption made by the programmer during the implementation of the program remains valid when the program is executed.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In Java, `%` is the *remainder* operator (*modulo*), and in Java, if its first operand is negative, the result can also be negative (unlike the modulo used in mathematics).
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer has assumed that `total` is non-negative, so that the remainder of a division by 2 will always be 0 or 1.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The assertion makes this assumption explicit: if `countNumberOfUsers` does return a negative value, the program may have a bug.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] A major advantage of this technique is that when an error does occur, it is detected immediately and directly, rather than later through often obscure effects.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Since an assertion failure usually reports the code location, one can often pinpoint the error without further debugging.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions are also sometimes placed at points where the execution is not supposed to reach.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] For example, assertions could be placed at the `default` clause of the `switch` statement in languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Any case that the programmer does not handle intentionally will raise an error, and the program will abort rather than silently continuing in an erroneous state.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In D such an assertion is added automatically when a `switch` statement doesn't contain a `default` clause.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In Java, assertions have been a part of the language since version 1.4.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertion failures result in raising an `AssertionError` when the program is run with the appropriate flags, without which the assert statements are ignored.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In C, they are added on by the standard header `<assert.h>` defining `assert(*assertion*)` as a macro that signals an error in the case of failure, usually terminating the program.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In C++, both `<assert.h>` and `<cassert>` headers provide the `assert` macro.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The danger of assertions is that they may cause side effects either by changing memory data or by changing thread timing.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions should be implemented carefully, so they cause no side effects on program code.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertion constructs in a language allow for easy test-driven development (TDD) without the use of a third-party library.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In C#, there is no assertion macro or keyword, but instead classes `System.Diagnostics.Debug` and `System.Diagnostics.Trace` which provide `Assert()` methods.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] During the development cycle, the programmer will typically run the program with assertions enabled.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] When an assertion failure occurs, the programmer is immediately notified of the problem.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Many assertion implementations will also halt the program's execution: this is useful, since if the program continued to run after an assertion violation occurred, it might corrupt its state and make the cause of the problem more difficult to locate.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Using the information provided by the assertion failure (such as the location of the failure and perhaps a stack trace, or even the full program state if the environment supports core dumps or if the program is running in a debugger), the programmer can usually fix the problem.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Thus, assertions provide a very powerful tool in debugging.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] When a program is deployed to production, assertions are typically turned off to avoid any overhead or side effects they may have.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In some cases, assertions are completely absent from deployed code, such as in C/C++ assertions via macros.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In other cases, such as Java, assertions are present in the deployed code and can be turned on in the field for debugging.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions may also be used to promise the compiler that a given edge condition is not actually reachable, thereby permitting certain optimizations that would not otherwise be possible.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In this case, disabling the assertions could actually reduce performance.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions that are checked at compile time are called static assertions.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Static assertions are particularly useful in compile-time template metaprogramming, but can also be used in low-level languages like C by introducing illegal code if (and only if) the assertion fails.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] C11 and C++11 support static assertions directly through `static_assert`.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because the compiler will not allow two case labels with the same constant.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:saml-deep/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] An **identity provider** (abbreviated **IdP**, **IDP**, or **idp**) is a system entity that creates, maintains, and manages identity information for principals and also provides authentication services to relying applications within a federation or distributed network.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] Identity providers offer user authentication as a service.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] Relying party applications, such as web applications, outsource the user authentication step to a trusted identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] Such a relying party application is said to be *federated*, that is, it consumes federated identity.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] An identity provider is “a trusted provider that lets you use single sign-on (SSO) to access other websites.” SSO enhances usability by reducing password fatigue.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] It also provides better security by decreasing the potential attack surface.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] Identity providers can facilitate connections between cloud computing resources and users, thus decreasing the need for users to re-authenticate when using mobile and roaming applications.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] OpenID Connect (OIDC) is an identity layer on top of OAuth.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] In the domain model associated with OIDC, an identity provider is a special type of OAuth 2.0 authorization server.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] Specifically, a system entity called an OpenID Provider issues JSON-formatted identity tokens to OIDC relying parties via a RESTful HTTP API.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] The Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is a set of profiles for exchanging authentication and authorization data across security domains.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] In the SAML domain model, an identity provider is a special type of authentication authority.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] Specifically, a SAML identity provider is a system entity that issues authentication assertions in conjunction with an SSO profile of SAML.
[src:saml-deep/identity-provider] A relying party that consumes these authentication assertions is called a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Some 30 individuals from more than 24 companies and organizations were involved in the creation of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In particular, and of special note, Liberty Alliance donated its Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF) specification to OASIS, which became the basis of the SAML 2.0 specification.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Thus SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of SAML 1.1, Liberty ID-FF 1.2 Archived 2021-02-24 at the Wayback Machine, and Shibboleth 1.3.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] An assertion is a package of information that supplies zero or more statements made by a SAML authority.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] SAML assertions are usually made about a subject, represented by the `<Subject>` element.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The SAML 2.0 specification defines three different kinds of assertion statements that can be created by a SAML authority.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] All SAML-defined statements are associated with a subject.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] An important type of SAML assertion is the so-called "bearer" assertion used to facilitate Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Here is an example of a short-lived bearer assertion issued by an identity provider (https://idp.example.org/SAML2) to a service provider (https://sp.example.com/SAML2).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The assertion includes both an Authentication Assertion `<saml:AuthnStatement>` and an Attribute Assertion `<saml:AttributeStatement>`, which presumably the service provider uses to make an access control decision.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The prefix `saml:` represents the SAML V2.0 assertion namespace.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The most important of these protocols—the Authentication Request Protocol—is discussed in detail below.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO Profiles are initiated by the Identity Provider (IDP), that is, an unsolicited `<samlp:Response>` element is transmitted from the identity provider to the service provider (via the browser).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In SAML 2.0, however, the flow begins at the service provider who issues an explicit authentication request to the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The resulting *Authentication Request Protocol* is a significant new feature of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The above `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` element, which implicitly requests an assertion containing an authentication statement, was evidently issued by a service provider (https://sp.example.com/SAML2) and subsequently presented to the identity provider (via the browser).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The identity provider authenticates the principal (if necessary) and issues an authentication response, which is transmitted back to the service provider (again via the browser).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] A SAML message is transmitted from one entity to another either *by value* or *by reference*.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] A reference to a SAML message is called an *artifact*.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The receiver of an artifact resolves the reference by sending a `<samlp:ArtifactResolve>` request directly to the issuer of the artifact, who then responds with the actual message referenced by the artifact.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In response, the service provider returns the SAML element referenced by the enclosed artifact.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] This protocol forms the basis of the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] For Web Browser SSO, the HTTP Redirect Binding and the HTTP POST Binding are commonly used.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] For example, the service provider may use HTTP Redirect to send a request while the identity provider uses HTTP POST to transmit the response.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] This example illustrates that an entity's choice of binding is independent of its partner's choice of binding.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] SAML protocol messages can be carried directly in the URL query string of an HTTP GET request.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Since the length of URLs is limited in practice, the HTTP Redirect binding is suitable for short messages, such as the `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` message.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Longer messages (e.g. those containing signed or encrypted SAML assertions, such as SAML Responses) are usually transmitted via other bindings such as the HTTP POST Binding.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] SAML requests or responses transmitted via HTTP Redirect have a `SAMLRequest` or `SAMLResponse` query string parameter, respectively.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Before it's sent, the message is deflated (without header and checksum), base64-encoded, and URL-encoded, in that order.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Upon receipt, the process is reversed to recover the original message.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The above message (formatted for readability) may be signed for additional security.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In practice, all the data contained in a `<samlp:AuthnRequest>`, such as `Issuer` which contains the SP ID, and `NameIDPolicy`, has been agreed between IdP and SP beforehand (via manual information exchange or via SAML metadata).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In that case signing the request is not a security constraint.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] When the `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` contains information not known by the IdP beforehand, such as Assertion Consumer Service URL, signing the request is recommended for security purposes.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] In the following example, both the service provider and the identity provider use an HTTP POST binding.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The value of the `SAMLRequest` parameter is the base64-encoding of a `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` element, which is transmitted to the identity provider via the browser.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The value of the `SAMLResponse` parameter is the base64 encoding of a `<samlp:Response>` element, which likewise is transmitted to the service provider via the browser.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] This assumes, of course, that the first form element in the page contains the above SAMLResponse containing `form` element (`forms[0]`).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The HTTP Artifact Binding uses the Artifact Resolution Protocol and the SAML SOAP Binding (over HTTP) to resolve a SAML message by reference.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Consider the following specific example.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Suppose a service provider wants to send a `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` message to an identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Next the identity provider sends a `<samlp:ArtifactResolve>` request (such as the ArtifactResolveRequest shown earlier) directly to the service provider via a back channel.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Of course the flow can go in the other direction as well, that is, the identity provider may issue an artifact, and in fact this is more common.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] See, for example, the "double artifact" profile example later in this topic.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Thus a SAML 2.0 artifact consists of three components: a two-byte `TypeCode`, a two-byte `EndpointIndex`, and an arbitrary sequence of bytes called the `RemainingArtifact`.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] These three pieces of information are concatenated and base64-encoded to yield the complete artifact.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The `TypeCode` uniquely identifies the artifact format.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] SAML 2.0 predefines just one such artifact, of type 0x0004.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The `EndpointIndex` is a reference to a particular artifact resolution endpoint managed by the artifact issuer (which may be either the IdP or the SP, as mentioned earlier).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The `RemainingArtifact`, which is determined by the type definition, is the "meat" of the artifact.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] Thus a type 0x0004 artifact is of size 44 bytes (unencoded).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The `SourceId` is an arbitrary sequence of bytes, although in practice, the `SourceId` is the SHA-1 hash of the issuer's entityID.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The `MessageHandle` is a random sequence of bytes that references a SAML message that the artifact issuer is willing to produce on-demand.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] If you look closely, you can see the `TypeCode` (0x0004) and the `EndpointIndex` (0x0000) at the front of the artifact.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The next 20 bytes are the SHA-1 hash of the issuer's entityID (https://idp.example.org/SAML2) followed by 20 random bytes.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p01] The base64-encoding of these 44 bytes is what you see in the ArtifactResolveRequest example above.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Although the number of supported profiles is quite large, the Profiles specification (SAMLProf) is simplified since the binding aspects of each profile have been factored out into a separate Bindings specification (SAMLBind).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] SAML 2.0 specifies a *Web Browser SSO Profile* involving an identity provider (IdP), a service provider (SP), and a principal wielding an HTTP user agent.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The service provider has four bindings from which to choose while the identity provider has three, which leads to twelve possible deployment scenarios.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] We outline three of those deployment scenarios below.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] This is one of the most common scenarios.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The service provider sends a SAML Request to the IdP SSO Service using the HTTP-Redirect Binding.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The identity provider returns the SAML Response to the SP Assertion Consumer Service using the HTTP-POST Binding.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The message flow begins with a request for a secured resource at the service provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The service provider performs a security check on behalf of the target resource.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] If a valid security context at the service provider already exists, skip steps 2–7.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The service provider may use any kind of mechanism to discover the identity provider that will be used, e.g., ask the user, use a preconfigured IdP, etc.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The service provider generates an appropriate SAMLRequest (and RelayState, if any), then redirects the browser to the IdP SSO Service using a standard HTTP 302 redirect.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The `RelayState` token is an opaque reference to state information maintained at the service provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The SAMLRequest may be signed using the SP signing key.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Typically, however, this is not necessary.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] where the values of the `SAMLRequest` and `RelayState` parameters are the same as those provided in the redirect.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The SSO Service at the identity provider processes the `<samlp:AuthnRequest>` element (by URL-decoding, base64-decoding and inflating the request, in that order) and performs a security check.
