[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] As a hypothetical example of a *Common Domain*, let's suppose Example UK (example.co.uk) and Example Deutschland (example.de) belong to the virtual organization Example Global Alliance (example.com).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] In this example, the domain **example.com** is the common domain.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Both Example UK and Example Deutschland have a presence in this domain (uk.example.com and de.example.com, resp.).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The *Common Domain Cookie* is a secure browser cookie scoped to the common domain.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] For each browser user, this cookie stores a history list of recently visited IdPs.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The name and value of the cookie are specified in the IdP Discovery Profile (SAMLProf).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] After a successful act of authentication, the IdP requests the *Common Domain Cookie Writing Service*.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] This service appends the IdP's unique identifier to the common domain cookie.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The SP, when it receives an unauthenticated request for a protected resource, requests the *Common Domain Cookie Reading Service* to discover the browser user's most recently used IdP.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The SAML SOAP binding is often used in conjunction with queries.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The *Attribute Query* is perhaps the most important type of SAML query.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Often a requester, acting on behalf of the principal, queries an identity provider for attributes.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Note that the `Issuer` is the `Subject` in this case.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] This is sometimes called an *attribute self-query*.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] In contrast to the BearerAssertion shown earlier, this assertion has a longer lifetime corresponding to the lifetime of the X.509 certificate that the principal used to authenticate to the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Moreover, since the assertion is signed, the user can push this assertion to a relying party, and as long as the user can prove possession of the corresponding private key (hence the name "holder-of-key"), the relying party can be assured that the assertion is authentic.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Quite literally, metadata is what makes SAML work (or work well).
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Metadata ensures a secure transaction between an identity provider and a service provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Before metadata, trust information was encoded into the implementation in a proprietary manner.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Now the sharing of trust information is facilitated by standard metadata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] SAML 2.0 provides a well-defined, interoperable metadata format that entities can leverage to bootstrap the trust process.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] By definition, an identity provider manages an SSO service that supports the SAML Web Browser SSO profile specified in SAMLProf.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] See, for example, the identity provider described in the `<md:IDPSSODescriptor>` element shown in the next section.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] The previous metadata element describes the SSO service at the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] As noted at the beginning of this section, the values of the `Location` attributes are used by a service provider to route SAML messages, which minimizes the possibility of a rogue identity provider orchestrating a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] By definition, a service provider manages an assertion consumer service that supports the SAML Web Browser SSO profile specified in SAMLProf.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] See, for example, the service provider described in the `<md:SPSSODescriptor>` element shown in the next section.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] As noted at the beginning of this section, the values of the `Location` attributes are used by an identity provider to route SAML messages, which minimizes the possibility of a rogue service provider orchestrating a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] In the previous examples, each `<md:EntityDescriptor>` element is shown to be digitally signed.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Typically metadata aggregates are published by trusted third parties called *federations* who vouch for the integrity of all the metadata in the aggregate.
[src:saml-deep/saml-2-0-p02] Note that metadata aggregates can be very large, composed of hundreds or even thousands of entities per aggregate.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The **SAML metadata** standard belongs to the family of XML-based standards known as the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) published by OASIS in 2005.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A SAML metadata document describes a SAML deployment such as a SAML identity provider or a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Deployments share metadata to establish a baseline of trust and interoperability.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To securely interoperate, partners share metadata in whatever form and by whatever means possible.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Every SAML system entity has an entity ID, a globally-unique identifier used in software configurations, relying-party databases, and client-side cookies.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] On the wire, every SAML protocol message contains the entity ID of the issuer.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] For authentication purposes, a SAML message may be digitally signed by the issuer.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To verify the signature on the message, the message receiver uses a public key known to belong to the issuer.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Similarly, to encrypt a message, a public encryption key belonging to the ultimate receiver must be known to the issuer.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In both situations—signing and encryption—trusted public keys must be shared in advance.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Once the message is signed and encrypted, the issuer sends the message to a trusted protocol endpoint, the location of which must be known in advance.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Upon receipt, the message receiver decrypts the message (using its own private decryption key) and verifies the signature (using a trusted public key in metadata) before mapping the entity ID in the message to a trusted partner.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The previous scenario requires each party to know the other in advance.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To establish a baseline of trust, parties share metadata with each other.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Initially, this may be as simple as sharing information via email.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Over time, as the number of SAML partners grows, the natural tendency is to automate the metadata sharing process.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To fully automate the metadata sharing process, a standard file format is needed.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To this end, the SAML V2.0 Metadata specification defines a standard representation for SAML metadata that simplifies the configuration of SAML software and makes it possible to create secure, automated processes for metadata sharing.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] As SAML technology has matured, the importance of SAML metadata has steadily increased.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Today an implementation that supports SAML web browser single sign-on requires a schema-valid SAML metadata file for each SAML partner.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The term *static metadata* refers to a metadata file that is configured directly into the SAML application by an administrator.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In doing so, the administrator becomes responsible for the maintenance of the metadata regardless of how the metadata was obtained in the first place.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Thus static metadata contributes to the overall static configuration of the SAML application.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Unfortunately, SAML metadata is inherently non-static as illustrated by the following typical scenario between a SAML identity provider (IdP) and a SAML service provider (SP).
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Suppose an IdP owner obtains SAML metadata from an SP partner.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Perhaps the SP metadata is transmitted to the IdP owner via email, or maybe the IdP owner logs into a protected web app and downloads the SP metadata via a browser.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Regardless of how the metadata is obtained, the result is the same: the IdP owner configures the SP metadata directly into the IdP software.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Now suppose the SP metadata contains a public encryption key.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Presumably, the corresponding private decryption key is configured into the SP software.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] If the private decryption key is compromised (or otherwise needs to be replaced), the public encryption key in the SP metadata is no longer trustworthy and must be replaced as well.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Since the SP metadata is statically configured in the IdP software, only the IdP owner can replace the public encryption key in the SP metadata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In this sense, *the IdP owner is responsible for the SP metadata.* This mismatch leads to interoperability issues.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] By statically configuring IdP metadata into the SP software, the SP owner implicitly accepts the responsibility to maintain the IdP metadata when something changes.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Since an IdP (or SP) typically has many partners, static metadata configuration clearly does not scale, and moreover, change management associated with static metadata is difficult at best.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Not surprisingly, metadata sharing processes yearn to be automated.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Every metadata file that is statically configured into the SAML application by an administrator incurs technical debt.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The accumulation of this debt prevents the SAML deployment from scaling to its potential.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To avoid excessive technical debt, the metadata sharing process must be automated.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] One approach is to enlist the help of a trusted third party whose responsibility it is to collect, curate, and distribute metadata across the network.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Curated metadata is consistently formatted, more likely to be free of vulnerabilities (intentional or otherwise), and therefore safe to use.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In the case of SAML metadata, this trusted third party is called a *SAML federation.* The community of SAML deployers comprising the federation willingly conform to one or more profiles of SAML to promote interoperability and trust.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] To that end, federation participants often share a central infrastructure for metadata sharing, which allows the federation to scale to thousands of interoperable SAML deployments.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Now let's retrace some of the steps that led to the publication of the SAML V2.0 Metadata specification in March 2005.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A turning point occurred on 14 November 2003—our story starts there.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In response to Microsoft Passport, the Liberty Alliance conceived the *Identity Federation Framework*, a federation technology developed over a three-year period between 2002 and 2004.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] (The previously mentioned history of SAML provides context for ID-FF.) On 14 November 2003, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] As it turns out, all of those goals were preserved in the OASIS SAML V2.0 Metadata Standard described later in this article.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The schema document included with the legacy Liberty ID-FF 1.2 archive is identified as Liberty Metadata Version 1.1 whereas Liberty Metadata Version 1.0 was contributed to OASIS.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The apparent contradiction was explained by the schema's author.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] (Peter Davis, Personal Communication) Between November 2003 (when Version 1.0 was contributed to OASIS) and December 2004 (when Version 1.1 was completed by Liberty), development of the Liberty metadata specification continued in parallel with the OASIS work stream.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] See the chart below for a visual representation.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The arrows in the chart indicate dependencies while the dashed lines indicate equivalencies.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Relevant references into the Liberty work stream are given at the end of this article.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The original metadata schema contributed to OASIS is listed in its entirety in section 7 of the Liberty Metadata Version 1.0 specification.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Similarly, the specification for Liberty Metadata Version 1.1 includes a listing of the Version 1.1 schema.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Both the Version 1.0 schema and the Version 1.1 schema are linked here courtesy of the Internet Archive's Wayback Machine.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Over the next thirteen months, from November 2003 to December 2004, the OASIS Security Services (SAML) Technical Committee (SSTC) molded the Liberty metadata specification into what eventually became known as SAML Metadata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] During that time, the SSTC generalized the metadata specification to include support for multiple protocols (including non-SAML protocols) but more importantly, the Liberty metadata schema was retrofitted with numerous extension points.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Historically, the extensibility of SAML Metadata has had important consequences, as we shall see.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] By March 2004, most of the Liberty contribution was incorporated into the OASIS work stream.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] From that point onward, the Liberty and OASIS work streams progressed concurrently (but not independently since the same people were working on both specifications).
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Between March and July 2004, the fledgling SAML Metadata specification underwent significant churn.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In July 2004, the SSTC issued a public call for comments covering a complete set of SAML V2.0 draft specifications.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Included in that specification set was a working draft of a newly forged SAML V2.0 Metadata specification.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In retrospect, it appears as though the bulk of the SAML V2.0 Metadata specification was developed between March and July 2004, but clearly the SAML V2.0 Metadata Standard sprung from the loins of the Liberty Alliance, specifically Liberty Metadata Version 1.0.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Consequently, to understand the origins of SAML Metadata, one must study the provenance of Liberty metadata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The remaining history of SAML Metadata is mostly OASIS administrative process.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] After the final Committee Draft was published in November 2004, the SSTC began the standardization process in January 2005.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Finally, on 5 March 2005, OASIS announced the newly ratified SAML V2.0 Standard.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The V2.0 specification set (see the References section for a complete list) included the final SAML V2.0 Metadata specification.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A decade later, in September 2015, OASIS published a revised SAML Metadata specification with errata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] As a result, the original metadata specification was deprecated, as were the other documents in the original 2.0 specification set.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] During the intervening decade, between 2005 and 2015, the SSTC developed a number of "Post-V2.0" draft specifications.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Some of these draft documents became Committee Specifications.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A select subset of these Committee Specifications are listed in the References section at the end of this article.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] As it turns out, the influence of the Liberty Identity Federation Framework on SAML Metadata predates the contribution of ID-FF 1.2 in November 2003.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Apparently the SSTC was dabbling in metadata in parallel with the Liberty Alliance.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The revision history at the end of that draft document gives the following characterization of itself: "Initial draft based on Draft 07 of SAML 1.1 Metadata specification." In other words, earlier draft documents were published.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Indeed, the revision history at the end of the previous draft shows a trail of metadata specifications dating back to November 2002.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Following the document trail, the influence of Liberty ID-FF on SAML metadata can be traced to a draft specification published in April 2003.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] This is the first known OASIS document that references Liberty ID-FF, specifically, Liberty Metadata Version 1.0-06, an early version of the Liberty Metadata specification about which little is known.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] It is, however, clear that "Metadata for SAML 1.1 Web Browser Profiles" was intended to be a companion to the SAML V1.1 Standard but of course we know that V1.1 does not specify the use of metadata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] See the next section for relevant conjecture.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] There is no evidence to suggest that either of these early attempts to define a metadata schema had any appreciable effect on the development of the Liberty metadata schema.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] We know that metadata standards for SAML V1.0 or SAML V1.1 were never published.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] We also know that the necessary IPR for Liberty Metadata was not in place until November 2003.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A draft specification entitled "Metadata for SAML 1.1 Web Browser Profiles" was the first known SAML metadata specification based on Liberty ID-FF.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The title of the draft specification makes it clear that the SSTC knew that SAML V1.1 was coming and moreover SAML metadata was to be included in the SAML V1.1 Standard.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Unfortunately that did not happen since the necessary IPR was not in place when the SAML V1.1 Standard was announced.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Indeed, the formal contribution of Liberty ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS occurred two months **after** the announcement of the SAML V1.1 Standard in September 2003.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] SAML Metadata came to life between March and July 2004.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The SSTC issued a public call for comments that included a candidate SAML Metadata specification.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The final SAML Metadata specification was included in the SAML V2.0 Standard specification set announced in March 2005.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] For the next 10 years, the specification documents evolved (but the schema remained stable).
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A specification for SAML V2.0 Metadata with Errata (SAMLMeta20Errata) was published in September 2015.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] As mentioned earlier, the SAML V2.0 Metadata Schema has numerous extension points.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] This feature led to a proliferation of "Post-V2.0" specifications that extended the standard in several directions.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In essence, the *Metadata Interoperability Profile* is an attempt to provide a workable key revocation mechanism for SAML federations.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Since its publication in August 2009, the *Metadata Interoperability Profile* has been a particularly influential document, especially in higher education (see, for example, the certificate-related requirements for deployers in one large R&E federation).
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Indeed, the key feature that distinguishes a scalable SAML implementation (from one that is not) is metadata interoperability.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In this section we give concrete examples of the SAML *entity descriptor,* the basic unit of policy and interoperability in SAML metadata.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Note that SAML metadata describes all parties involved in metadata-driven SAML Web Browser SSO except the browser user.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The all-important role descriptor has been omitted from this initial example for brevity.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The SAML metadata specification defines numerous concrete instances of the **md:RoleDescriptor** abstract type (section 2.4.1 of SAMLMeta).
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The two most important roles are described by the `<md:IDPSSODescriptor>` element and the `<md:SPSSODescriptor>` element.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Each of these role descriptors is illustrated in the subsections below.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A SAML identity provider manages a Single Sign-On Service endpoint that receives authentication requests from service providers.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The entity descriptor for an identity provider in that role contains an `<md:IDPSSODescriptor>` element, which itself contains at least one `<md:SingleSignOnService>` endpoint.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The content of the `<md:IDPSSODescriptor>` element describes the Single Sign-On Service at the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The values of the `md:SingleSignOnService/@Location` attributes in identity provider metadata are used by a service provider to route SAML messages, which minimizes the possibility of a rogue identity provider orchestrating a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] A SAML service provider manages an Assertion Consumer Service endpoint that receives authentication assertions from identity providers.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The entity descriptor for a service provider in that role contains an `<md:SPSSODescriptor>` element, which itself contains at least one `<md:AssertionConsumerService>` endpoint.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The content of the `<md:SPSSODescriptor>` element describes the Assertion Consumer Service at the service provider.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The value of the `md:AssertionConsumerService/@Location` attribute in service provider metadata is used by an identity provider to route SAML messages, which minimizes the possibility of a rogue service provider orchestrating a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The following SAML protocol flow is intended to illustrate the use of metadata at various stages of SAML web browser SSO.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Trusted SAML metadata ensures a secure transaction between a SAML identity provider (IdP) and a SAML service provider (SP).
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The SAML 2.0 Metadata Standard provides a well-defined, interoperable metadata format that entities can use to bootstrap the trust process.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The following sequence illustrates the use of SAML metadata to drive the SAML protocol flow.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] If a valid security context for the user principal already exists at the service provider, skip steps 2–13.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Before the service provider can initiate the SAML protocol flow at step 6, the browser user's preferred identity provider must be known.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Note that the SP `entityID` is included in the redirect URL as specified by the discovery protocol.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The Discovery Service discovers the browser user's preferred identity provider by unspecified means.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Note that the IdP `entityID` is included in the redirect URL as specified by the discovery protocol.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] For an outline how to construct the query string, see the corresponding SAML protocol flow in the SAML 2.0 article.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The identity provider returns a login page to the user's browser.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] At this point, the identity provider knows the identity of the user principal and so the identity provider constructs a SAML Assertion on behalf of the user principal.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] For a concrete example of such an Assertion, see the corresponding SAML protocol flow in the SAML 2.0 article.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] As always, refer to SAMLCore for details.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The `<saml:NameID>` element in the SAML Assertion encodes an identifier for the user principal.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] In this case, the identity provider includes a SAML2 Transient NameID (SAMLCore) in the SAML Assertion.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The identity provider includes two user attributes in the SAML Assertion: `eduPersonUniqueId` and `mail`.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Operationally, the identity provider digitally signs and encrypts the SAML Assertion, wraps the Assertion in a SAML Response, and then signs the Response object as well.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Typically the identity provider signs the Response alone but in this case both the Assertion and the Response are digitally signed.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] The identity provider returns an XHTML document to the user's browser.
[src:saml-deep/saml-metadata] Since a security context exists, the service provider returns the resource to the browser user agent as requested.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] An important use case that SAML addresses is web-browser single sign-on (SSO).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Single sign-on is relatively easy to accomplish within a security domain (using cookies, for example) but extending SSO across security domains is more difficult and resulted in the proliferation of non-interoperable proprietary technologies.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML Web Browser SSO profile was specified and standardized to promote interoperability.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In practice, SAML SSO is most commonly used for authentication into cloud-based business software.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML specification defines three roles: the principal (typically a human user), the identity provider (IdP) and the service provider (SP).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In the primary use case addressed by SAML, the principal requests a service from the service provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider requests and obtains an authentication assertion from the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] On the basis of this assertion, the service provider can make an access control decision, that is, it can decide whether to perform the service for the connected principal.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] At the heart of the SAML assertion is a subject (a principal within the context of a particular security domain) about which something is being asserted.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The subject is usually (but not necessarily) a human.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] As in the SAML 2.0 Technical Overview, the terms subject and principal are used interchangeably.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Before delivering the subject-based assertion from Identity Provider to the Service Provider, the Identity Provider may request some information from the principal (such as a user name and password) in order to authenticate the principal.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML specifies the content of the assertion that is passed from the Identity Provider to the Service Provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML, one Identity Provider may provide SAML assertions to many Service Providers.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Similarly, one Service Provider (SP) may rely on and trust assertions from many independent Identity Providers (IdP).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML does not specify the method of authentication at the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The IdP may use a username and password, or some other form of authentication, including multi-factor authentication or Kerberos tickets.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A directory service such as RADIUS or LDAP that allows users to log in with a user name and password is a typical source of authentication tokens at an identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The popular Internet social networking services also provide identity services that in theory could be used to support SAML exchanges.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Building on these initial contributions, in November 2002 OASIS announced the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 1.0 specification as an OASIS Standard.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Meanwhile, the Liberty Alliance, a large consortium of companies, non-profit and government organizations, proposed an extension to the SAML standard called the Liberty Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Like its SAML predecessor, Liberty ID-FF proposed a standardized, cross-domain, web-based, single sign-on framework.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition, Liberty described a *circle of trust* where each participating domain is trusted to accurately document the processes used to identify a user, the type of authentication system used, and any policies associated with the resulting authentication credentials.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Other members of the circle of trust could then examine these policies to determine whether to trust such information.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] While Liberty was developing ID-FF, the SSTC began work on a minor upgrade to the SAML standard.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting SAML 1.1 specification was ratified by the SSTC in September 2003.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Then, in November of that same year, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS, thereby sowing the seeds for the next major version of SAML.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In March 2005, SAML 2.0 was announced as an OASIS Standard.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of Liberty ID-FF and proprietary extensions contributed by the Shibboleth project, as well as early versions of SAML itself.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Most SAML implementations support v2.0 while many still support v1.1 for backward compatibility.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] By January 2008, deployments of SAML 2.0 became common in government, higher education, and commercial enterprises worldwide.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML has undergone one minor and one major revision since 1.0.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Versions 1.0 and 1.1 of SAML are similar even though small differences exist., however, the differences between SAML 2.0 and SAML 1.1 are substantial.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Although the two standards address the same use case, SAML 2.0 is incompatible with its predecessor.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Although ID-FF 1.2 was contributed to OASIS as the basis of SAML 2.0, there are some important differences between SAML 2.0 and ID-FF 1.2.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, the two specifications, despite their common roots, are incompatible.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML defines XML-based assertions and protocols, bindings, and profiles.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The term *SAML Core* refers to the general syntax and semantics of SAML assertions as well as the protocol used to request and transmit those assertions from one system entity to another.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] *SAML protocol* refers to **what** is transmitted, not **how** (the latter is determined by the choice of binding).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] So SAML Core defines "bare" SAML assertions along with SAML request and response elements.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML binding* determines how SAML requests and responses map onto standard messaging or communications protocols.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] An important (synchronous) binding is the SAML SOAP binding.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML profile* is a concrete manifestation of a defined use case using a particular combination of assertions, protocols and bindings.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML assertions are usually transferred from identity providers to service providers.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Assertions contain *statements* that service providers use to make access-control decisions.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute statement* asserts that a principal is associated with certain attributes.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute* is simply a name–value pair.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Relying parties use attributes to make access-control decisions.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] An *authorization decision statement* asserts that a principal is permitted to perform action *A* on resource *R* given evidence *E*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The expressiveness of authorization decision statements in SAML is intentionally limited.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] More-advanced use cases are encouraged to use XACML instead.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *protocol* describes how certain SAML elements (including assertions) are packaged within SAML request and response elements, and gives the processing rules that SAML entities must follow when producing or consuming these elements.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] For the most part, a SAML protocol is a simple request-response protocol.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important type of SAML protocol request is called a *query*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A service provider makes a query directly to an identity provider over a secure back channel.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Thus query messages are typically bound to SOAP.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The result of an attribute query is a SAML response containing an assertion, which itself contains an attribute statement.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] See the SAML 2.0 topic for an example of attribute query/response.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Beyond queries, SAML 1.1 specifies no other protocols.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 expands the notion of *protocol* considerably.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Most of these protocols are new in SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *binding* is a mapping of a SAML protocol message onto standard messaging formats and/or communications protocols.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, the SAML SOAP binding specifies how a SAML message is encapsulated in a SOAP envelope, which itself is bound to an HTTP message.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies just one binding, the SAML SOAP Binding.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition to SOAP, implicit in SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO are the precursors of the HTTP POST Binding, the HTTP Redirect Binding, and the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] These are not defined explicitly, however, and are only used in conjunction with SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The notion of binding is not fully developed until SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 completely separates the binding concept from the underlying profile.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *profile* describes in detail how SAML assertions, protocols, and bindings combine to support a defined use case.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important SAML profile is the Web Browser SSO Profile.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies two forms of Web Browser SSO, the Browser/Artifact Profile and the Browser/POST Profile.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter passes assertions *by value* whereas Browser/Artifact passes assertions *by reference*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] As a consequence, Browser/Artifact requires a back-channel SAML exchange over SOAP.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, all flows begin with a request at the identity provider for simplicity.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Proprietary extensions to the basic IdP-initiated flow have been proposed (by Shibboleth, for example).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The Web Browser SSO Profile was completely refactored for SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Conceptually, SAML 1.1 Browser/Artifact and Browser/POST are special cases of SAML 2.0 Web Browser SSO.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter is considerably more flexible than its SAML 1.1 counterpart due to the new "plug-and-play" binding design of SAML 2.0.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Unlike previous versions, SAML 2.0 browser flows begin with a request at the service provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] This provides greater flexibility, but SP-initiated flows naturally give rise to the so-called *Identity Provider Discovery* problem, the focus of much research today.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Requirements are often phrased in terms of (mutual) authentication, integrity, and confidentiality, leaving the choice of security mechanism to implementers and deployers.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The primary SAML use case is called *Web Browser Single Sign-On (SSO)*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] A user utilizes a *user agent* (usually a web browser) to request a web resource protected by a SAML *service provider*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the requesting user, issues an authentication request to a SAML *identity provider* through the user agent.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting protocol flow is depicted in the following diagram.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a GET request to the SSO service at the URL from step 2.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] URL query parameter) and performs a security check.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a POST request to the assertion consumer service at the service provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] parameter is taken from the XHTML form at step 4.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, the flow begins with a request to the identity provider's inter-site transfer service at step 3.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In the example flow above, all depicted exchanges are *front-channel exchanges*, that is, an HTTP user agent (browser) communicates with a SAML entity at each step.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, there are no *back-channel exchanges* or direct communications between the service provider and the identity provider.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Front-channel exchanges lead to simple protocol flows where all messages are passed *by value* using a simple HTTP binding (GET or POST).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Indeed, the flow outlined in the previous section is sometimes called the *Lightweight Web Browser SSO Profile*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Alternatively, for increased security or privacy, messages may be passed *by reference*.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, an identity provider may supply a reference to a SAML assertion (called an *artifact*) instead of transmitting the assertion directly through the user agent.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Subsequently, the service provider requests the actual assertion via a back channel.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Such a back-channel exchange is specified as a SOAP message exchange (SAML over SOAP over HTTP).
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] In general, any SAML exchange over a secure back channel is conducted as a SOAP message exchange.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] On the back channel, SAML specifies the use of SOAP 1.1.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] The use of SOAP as a binding mechanism is optional, however.
[src:saml-deep/security-assertion-markup-language] Any given SAML deployment will choose whatever bindings are appropriate.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:saml-deep/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
